Feature Engineering Audit

This section audits the engineered feature set to ensure:

  • Features are correctly specified
  • Values are plausible
  • Categorical values match metadata
  • Bins (AgeBand, FareBand) look reasonable
  • Derived features (FamilySize, FarePerPerson, TicketGroupSize, etc.) are correct
  • Missingness indicators behave as expected
  • Interactions take sensible values

We use descriptive statistics, bar charts, histograms, boxplots, and cross-tabs.

def summarize_feature_types(df):
    """
    Summarize feature types, unique counts, missingness,
    and add a description column for each feature.
    """

    FEATURE_DESCRIPTIONS = {

        # Target
        "Survived": "Target variable (0 = did not survive, 1 = survived)",

        # Core demographics
        "Pclass": "Passenger class (1 = upper, 2 = middle, 3 = lower)",
        "Sex": "Passenger sex (female/male)",
        "Age": "Imputed passenger age (continuous)",

        # Missingness indicators
        "AgeMissing": "Indicator (1 = Age originally missing, 0 = present)",
        "FareMissing": "Indicator (1 = Fare originally missing, 0 = present)",
        "CabinKnown": "Indicator (1 = Cabin present in raw data)",

        # Family structure
        "SibSp": "Number of siblings/spouses aboard",
        "Parch": "Number of parents/children aboard",
        "FamilySize": "Family size = SibSp + Parch + 1",
        "IsAlone": "Indicator (1 = FamilySize == 1)",

        # Fare transformations
        "Fare": "Passenger fare (imputed, continuous)",
        "LogFare": "Natural log transform of (Fare + 1)",
        "FarePerPerson": "Fare divided by FamilySize",

        # Ticket-derived engineered features
        "Ticket_strong": "Cleaned ticket identifier based on prefix & numeric body",
        "TicketPrefix": "Extracted ticket prefix category",
        "TicketGroupSize": "Number of passengers sharing the same Ticket_strong value",
        "TicketGroupFarePerPerson": "Fare divided by TicketGroupSize",

        # Embarked / Cabin / Title
        "Embarked": "Port of embarkation (C, Q, S)",
        "CabinDeck": "Extracted cabin deck letter (AG, T, Unknown)",
        "Title": "Passenger title extracted from name (Mr, Mrs, Miss, Master, Officer, Royalty)",

        # Binned variables
        "AgeBand": "Quantile-based age bin using training-set bin edges",
        "FareBand": "Quantile-based fare bin using training-set bin edges",

        # Interaction features
        "Sex_Pclass": "Interaction: Sex  Pclass",
        "Sex_AgeBand": "Interaction: Sex  AgeBand",
        "Embarked_Pclass": "Interaction: Embarked  Pclass",
        "Title_AgeBand": "Interaction: Title  AgeBand",
        "Pclass_FareBand": "Interaction: Pclass  FareBand",
    }

    # Base summary table
    summary = pd.DataFrame({
        "dtype": df.dtypes,
        "n_unique": df.nunique(),
        "missing": df.isna().sum(),
    })

    summary["missing_pct"] = summary["missing"] / len(df) * 100

    # Add descriptions
    summary["description"] = summary.index.map(
        lambda col: FEATURE_DESCRIPTIONS.get(col, "No description available.")
    )

    # Sorting helpers
    summary["dtype_str"] = summary["dtype"].astype(str)
    summary["is_target"] = (summary.index == "Survived")

    # Sort: features first, target last
    summary = summary.sort_values(
        by=["is_target", "dtype_str"],
        ascending=[True, True]
    )

    return summary.drop(columns=["dtype_str", "is_target"])

In[10]:
def plot_numeric_feature(col, df, df_target=None):
    """
    Plot histogram + boxplot for a single numeric feature.
    If df_target is provided, also plot Survived-conditioned boxplots.
    """
    # --- Coerce numeric safely ---
    numeric_data = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce").dropna()
    if numeric_data.empty:
        print(f"Skipping {col}: no numeric data.")
        return

    # =======================================================
    # 1. Basic distribution (Histogram + Boxplot)
    # =======================================================
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 3))

    # Histogram
    sns.histplot(numeric_data, bins=40, kde=True, ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f"Histogram: {col}")

    # Boxplot (Matplotlib only)
    axes[1].boxplot(numeric_data, vert=False)
    axes[1].set_title(f"Boxplot: {col}")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    # =======================================================
    # 2. Target-conditioned boxplots (if df_target exists)
    # =======================================================
    if df_target is not None and col != "Survived":
        if "Survived" not in df_target.columns:
            print("Warning: Survived not found in df_target.")
            return
        
        # Extract groups
        g0 = df_target.loc[df_target["Survived"] == 0, col].dropna()
        g1 = df_target.loc[df_target["Survived"] == 1, col].dropna()

        # Skip if both groups empty
        if g0.empty and g1.empty:
            print(f"Skipping {col}: no target-conditioned data.")
            return

        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))

        ax.boxplot(
            [g0, g1],
            tick_labels=["Survived = 0", "Survived = 1"],
            vert=True
        )
        ax.set_title(f"{col}: Distribution by Survived")

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()


# =======================================================
# RUN OVER ALL NUMERIC FEATURES
# =======================================================
for col in numeric_features:
    plot_numeric_feature(col, train_fe, df_target=train_fe)

from IPython.display import display

def quick_check(col, df):
    print(f"\n=== {col} ===")
    print("dtype:", df[col].dtype)
    print("n_unique:", df[col].nunique())
    print("missing:", df[col].isna().sum())

    # Sample values (random every run)
    try:
        sample_vals = df[col].dropna().sample(
            min(10, df[col].nunique())
        ).tolist()
    except ValueError:
        sample_vals = []
    print("sample values:", sample_vals)

    # Show 5 random full observations (random every run)
    print("\nSample observations (5 rows):")
    display(df.sample(5))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

def plot_band_counts(df, col, figsize=(10,4)):
    """
    Plots the frequency counts for interval-based categorical features
    such as AgeBand and FareBand, without warnings.
    """

    # Convert interval categories to string labels for safe plotting
    counts = df[col].value_counts().sort_index()
    labels = counts.index.astype(str)  # avoid warnings from interval dtype

    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    sns.barplot(x=labels, y=counts.values, color="steelblue")
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")
    plt.title(f"Distribution of {col}")
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel("Count")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Plot AgeBand and FareBand
plot_band_counts(train_fe, "AgeBand")
plot_band_counts(train_fe, "FareBand")
